<section xml:id="complements">
  <title>Complements</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>S</m> be a set, and let <m>T \subseteq S</m> be a subset.
        Then the <term>complement</term> of <m>T</m> in <m>S</m> is the subset
        <me>
          S \setminus T = \{ x \in S : x \notin T \} \subseteq S
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    Assume that the subset <m>T \subseteq S</m> is identified using set-builder notation:
    <me>
      T = \{x \in S : A(x) \}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Then we can do the same for its complement by using negation:
    <me>
      S \setminus T = \{x \in S : \overline{A}(x)\}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the set of even integers:
        <me>
          T = \{n \in \mathbb{Z} : 2\text{ divides } n\} \subseteq \mathbb{Z}
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Its complement in <m>\mathbb{Z}</m> is the set of odd integers:
        <me>
          \mathbb{Z} \setminus T = \{n \in \mathbb{Z} : 2\text{ does not divide } n\} \subseteq \mathbb{Z}
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the subset
        <me>
          S = \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : x \geq 0 \}
        </me>,
        the set of real numbers no less than <m>0</m>.
        Its complement in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> is
        <me>
          \mathbb{R} \setminus S = \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : x \lt  0 \}
        </me>,
        the set of real numbers less than <m>0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</section>